Throughout my career I’ve had the opportunity to meet some amazing, experienced men in the industry. I’m happy to have recently gained another mentor, Ron. He worked in the “right” generation of logging, has cut old growth redwoods, worked all over the west coast, and has probably witnessed some of the best and some of the worst. Myself, as someone who is not only a bit unconventional in this industry, but has an unconventional background (I’m from the Midwest, have a background in climbing, I’m not second or third generation, etc), I’m never sure how I’ll be perceived. Sometimes it can be intimidating meeting such experienced and long time men in the industry. But Ron is up there as one of the nicest, most accepting, and intelligent men I’ve gotten to work with. Ego can run rampant in the industry, but not with him. He is humble and willing to extend his knowledge to help. He advocates for taking the time to make a nice stump, and that the smooth and steady folks with quality work and good decision making end up being the fastest in the long run, something that I resonated with continuing to work on. Very thankful for the opportunity to hang out with him for a couple of weeks, as I know not everyone who works for him gets to do. This picture is from a gnarly rotten back leaner we jacked over. Until next time! 🙏🏼
📸: @fmecky

Let me introduce ✨Annie Oakley✨ A little thing about myself I don’t think I’ve ever shared in a post is that Annie is my 4th great aunt. I grew up constantly hearing stories about her and seeing her belongings that my family still has. There’s a museum in Greenville, Ohio that my relatives have donated many items to. I’ve always been proud to share her DNA. She was no doubt a leading lady of her time known for her sharp shooting skills. Not everyone knows of her, though. So here are some facts:
✨She was born in 1860 in Darke County, Ohio (where I’m also from). 
✨She developed her shooting skills starting at the age of 8 in order to hunt food and provide for her family that lived in poverty.
✨At 15 she won shooting contest against her future husband, Frank Butler, an older and experienced marksmen.  He went on to essentially turn the spotlight onto Annie and managed her performances. 
✨She eventually joined Buffalo Bill Cody’s Wild West show, which she traveled with for the following 17 years.
✨Native American warrior Sitting Bull was very fond of Annie and adopted her. He gave her the name Watanya Cicilla which translates to “Little Sure Shot”. This became her famous nick name. 
✨I named the business I own with @fmecky Sure Shot Forestry to commemorate her 😊

didn’t take this for granted! 🙏🏻 Almost a week now since ending the redwood job. The night before we left the coast I met up with a couple of foresters that helped plan this job (thanks IG for introducing us 🙃). They shared that this was some of the nicest redwood they had seen. Don’t get me wrong, it wasn’t all this size (of course I share the good ones on here), but on average there was nicer timber than you typically come across on cutting sites these days, or so I’ve heard. To have the opportunity to add this to my timber cutting bucket list was a dream. I might not get a chance to cut redwood like this again until I’m an old timer myself. 
Not sure what’s next now cutting wise, but until then I’m eager to share a few more nice trees from this job 😊 I’ll miss it!
